<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="418" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,510,1041]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,287,510,536]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Comments.</emphasis>
As indicated in 
<bibRefCitation author="Mecho, A. &amp; Easton, E. E. &amp; Sellanes, J. &amp; Gorny, M. &amp; Mah, C." box="[482,712,511,537]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" pagination="91" refId="ref30588" refString="Mecho, A., Easton, E. E., Sellanes, J., Gorny, M. &amp; Mah, C. (2019) Unexplored diversity of the mesophotic echinoderm fauna of the Easter Island ecoregion. Marine Biology, 166, 91 https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00227 - 019 - 3537 - x" type="journal article" year="2019">
Mecho 
<emphasis box="[569,621,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">et al</emphasis>
. (2019)
</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1841" box="[722,878,511,537]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Goniasteridae</taxonomicName>
sp. C suggests 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Clark &amp; McKnight" authorityYear="2001" box="[1061,1301,511,537]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Ceramaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[1061,1301,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Ceramaster australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, previously known only from Macquarie Ridge and New Caledonian waters (H.E.S. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. E. S. &amp; McKnight, D. G." box="[955,1232,547,573]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" pagination="1 - 270" refId="ref27367" refString="Clark, H. E. S. &amp; McKnight, D. G. (2001) The marine fauna of New Zealand: Echinodermata: Asteroidea (Sea-stars), Order Valvatida. NIWA Biodiversity Memoir, 117, 1 - 270." type="journal article" year="2001">Clark &amp; McKnight 2001</bibRefCitation>
). This species was observed off Rapa Nui between 
<quantity box="[517,648,583,609]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" metricValueMax="2.8" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" unit="m" value="220.0" valueMax="280.0" valueMin="160.0">
160– 
<specimenCount box="[572,648,583,609]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" type="generic">280 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mecho, A. &amp; Easton, E. E. &amp; Sellanes, J. &amp; Gorny, M. &amp; Mah, C." box="[660,880,583,609]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" pagination="91" refId="ref30588" refString="Mecho, A., Easton, E. E., Sellanes, J., Gorny, M. &amp; Mah, C. (2019) Unexplored diversity of the mesophotic echinoderm fauna of the Easter Island ecoregion. Marine Biology, 166, 91 https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00227 - 019 - 3537 - x" type="journal article" year="2019">
Mecho 
<emphasis box="[746,803,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">et al.</emphasis>
(2019
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<figureCitation box="[892,992,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="34.[151,250,1942,1966]" captionTargetBox="[314,1275,238,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-62@34.[312,1275,237,1918]" captionTargetPageId="34" captionText="FIGURE 14. Ophidiaster agassizi USNM E46260 (Juan Fernandez Islands, Chile): A. Abactinal view. Scale bar equals 1.5 cm. B. Abactinal surface close-up. Scale bar equals 0.4 cm. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar equals 1.5 cm. Inset scale bar equals 1.0 mm. D. Actinal surface showing furrow spination. Scale bar equals 0.4 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4896933" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4896933/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Fig. 14C</figureCitation>
) and 
<figureCitation box="[1057,1140,583,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,244,1842]" captionTargetId="figure-57@16.[151,1436,237,1849]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 6. Anthenoides epixanthus and Goniasteridae “C” (Rapa Nui): A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. B. Abactinal surface interradial paired plates. Scale bar equals 0. 25 cm. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. D. Actinal surface close-up, oral region. Scale bar equals 0.2 cm. E. Rapa Nui Goniasteridae “C” (similar to Ceramaster australis) feeding on fallen antipatharian. Image Courtesy A. Mecho." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4896907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4896907/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Fig. 6E</figureCitation>
(herein) displays strongly convex superomarginal plates with curved edges, which are darker in color, and in contact laterally between plates, as is seen in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Clark &amp; McKnight" authorityYear="2001" box="[293,423,655,681]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Ceramaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[293,423,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">C. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[439,526,655,682]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,244,1842]" captionTargetId="figure-57@16.[151,1436,237,1849]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 6. Anthenoides epixanthus and Goniasteridae “C” (Rapa Nui): A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. B. Abactinal surface interradial paired plates. Scale bar equals 0. 25 cm. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. D. Actinal surface close-up, oral region. Scale bar equals 0.2 cm. E. Rapa Nui Goniasteridae “C” (similar to Ceramaster australis) feeding on fallen antipatharian. Image Courtesy A. Mecho." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4896907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4896907/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Fig. 6E</figureCitation>
). Images of “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1841" box="[673,832,655,681]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Goniasteridae</taxonomicName>
sp. C” Strongly suggest 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Clark &amp; McKnight" authorityYear="2001" box="[1110,1348,655,681]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Ceramaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[1110,1348,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Ceramaster australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but image quality is imperfect and characters such as the elongate superomarginal plate shape and body color appear to differ from descriptions of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Clark &amp; McKnight" authorityYear="2001" box="[454,585,727,753]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Ceramaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis box="[454,585,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">C. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,510,1041]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,449,762,788]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Feeding observation.</emphasis>
A further observation of “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1841" box="[748,907,763,789]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Goniasteridae</taxonomicName>
C” from Rapa Nui (
<figureCitation box="[1141,1228,763,790]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,244,1842]" captionTargetId="figure-57@16.[151,1436,237,1849]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 6. Anthenoides epixanthus and Goniasteridae “C” (Rapa Nui): A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. B. Abactinal surface interradial paired plates. Scale bar equals 0. 25 cm. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. D. Actinal surface close-up, oral region. Scale bar equals 0.2 cm. E. Rapa Nui Goniasteridae “C” (similar to Ceramaster australis) feeding on fallen antipatharian. Image Courtesy A. Mecho." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4896907" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4896907/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Fig. 6E</figureCitation>
) shows it on what appears to be a fallen stalk of a “black coral” or antipatharian. Polyps on the stalk are fully extended on one side of the star but absent on the other side with the star showing an upward curvature around the stalk. This appears to be feeding by the goniasterid on the polyps of the antipatharian. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bo, M &amp; Canese, S. &amp; Bavestrello, G." box="[876,1055,871,897]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" pagination="2009 - 2012" refId="ref26750" refString="Bo, M, Canese, S. &amp; Bavestrello, G. (2018) On the coral-feeding habit of the sea star Peltaster placenta. Marine Biodiversity, 49, 2009 - 2012. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 12526 - 018 - 0931 - 4" type="journal article" year="2018">
Bo 
<emphasis box="[916,966,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">et al</emphasis>
. (2018)
</bibRefCitation>
has reported on a similar Atlantic species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="J. Muller &amp; Troschel" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[246,450,907,933]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Peltaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="17" pageNumber="418" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[246,450,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Peltaster placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, feeding on an antipatharian.
</paragraph>
